  "text": "Routine staining may lead to misinterpretation and often does not reveal all the mast cells in examined specimens. Histochemical techniques (toluidine blue staining) partially reduce the risk of erroneous assessment, but the best method to identify mast cells seems to be immunohistochemical staining. However, immunohistochemical examination revealed that the population of mast cells around the tumor is not homogeneous. In some cells tryptase and chymase expression were observed, while others expressed only tryptase, which allows us to distinguish two subpopulations of potentially divergent biological influence on the neoplasm [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
